The Ranch Hand study will follow until 2006 the health of 1,300 Air Force personnel who sprayed Agent Orange in Vietnam to defoliate swaths of Vietnam's jungles and deprive North Vietnamese troops of cover.
An Air Force study of veterans who sprayed Agent Orange during the Vietnam War found the strongest evidence to date that exposure to the herbicide is associated with diabetes, officials said today.
Defoliants -- including Agent Orange with its highly toxic component dioxin -- were sprayed over central and southern Vietnam during the war to eliminate cover for the Viet Cong and North Vietnamese army.
